654. Brain Res. 1987 Jul;388(2):99-103. doi: 10.1016/s0006-8993(87)80002-1.

Regulation of tyrosine hydroxylase gene expression during differentiation of 
neuroblastoma cells.

Summerhill EM, Wood K, Fishman MC.

Differentiation of N1E-115 neuroblastoma cells into neuron-like cells, with 
extension of neurites and acquisition of excitable membranes, can be induced by 
dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). We have found this differentiation to be accompanied 
by an increase in tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) mRNA, an increase disproportionate 
to changes in mRNAs for other measured, non-neuron-specific genes. The mRNA 
increases slowly over several days and falls gradually after removal of DMSO. 
Nuclear run-on studies suggest that a change in the rate of transcription cannot 
explain the increase in steady-state mRNA levels. TH mRNA half-life does, 
however, increase. This suggests that regulation is exerted in this case not at 
the level of transcription but rather at that of mRNA stability.

